<h3><span id="Forget_about_the_cold_and_fatigue_with_a_footbath"><b>Forget about the cold and fatigue with a footbath.</b></span></h3>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3907" src="https://japanbusonline.com/bus-repo/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/image2-2.jpg" alt="ikaho-onsen-ishidangai" width="443" height="591" srcset="https://japanbusonline.com/bus-repo/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/image2-2.jpg 443w, https://japanbusonline.com/bus-repo/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/image2-2-225x300.jpg 225w" sizes="(max-width: 443px) 100vw, 443px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Even if it is merely a day trip, it would be a shame not to take a dip in a hot spring in a place famous for its hot springs. This is where footbaths come in.</span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3823" src="https://japanbusonline.com/bus-repo/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/image3-2.jpg" alt="" width="591" height="443" srcset="https://japanbusonline.com/bus-repo/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/image3-2.jpg 591w, https://japanbusonline.com/bus-repo/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/image3-2-300x225.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 591px) 100vw, 591px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">At the 212th step of the stone staircase, there is a footbath called Tatsu no Yu at Kishigon Ryokan, which is open to everyone free of charge. You can soak up to your calves in this footbath, which quickly warmed me up and relieved my fatigue.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">By the way&#8230;the reason why the water looks brown is because the hot water flowers (an ingredient found in natural hot springs) have hardened. It seems to have an extra healing effect, doesn&#8217;t it?</span></p>
<p><b>Basic information about Kishigon Ryokan Tatsu no Yu</b></p>
